{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516520"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:43:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:43:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12644"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12644"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.02,0.69,0.25,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5127"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77574"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5127","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5127"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12644"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63087"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"1803"},{"type":"tags","id":"8840"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8600"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9102"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26649"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26666"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77574"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after accidentally getting splashed in the eye with an alkali solution while working in a chemical factory. He complains of severe pain, redness, and blurry vision in his left eye. On examination, the left eye appears red, inflamed, and oedematous. The cornea shows signs of haze and epithelial loss. The visual acuity in the left eye is 6/60.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical anaesthetic drops","Topical prednisolone drops","Irrigation with normal saline","Irrigation with sterile water","Topical cycloplegic drops"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient presented after getting a splash of alkali in his left eye while working in a factory. \u003Cstrong\u003EIrrigating the affected eye with normal saline\u003C/strong\u003E is the best initial management of an alkali burn in the eye. This should be done immediately after the patient presents to the emergency department to remove any residual alkali and minimise tissue damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EApplying \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical anaesthetic drops\u003C/strong\u003E can provide temporary pain relief but is not the best initial management of an alkali burn in the eye. Immediate irrigation is crucial to prevent further damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETopical steroids such as \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical prednisolone drops\u003C/strong\u003E are used to minimise the inflammation and therefore the secondary damage to the ocular tissue following a chemical burn. However, it is not the initial step of management. Use of steroid drops following a chemical burn is restricted to the first week to 10 days as longer duration of steroid use may delay healing and impede epithelial regeneration and migration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIrrigation with sterile water\u003C/strong\u003E is less effective than normal saline for chemical burns as it may not adequately neutralise the alkali. Normal saline is preferred for its isotonic properties, which help to minimise further irritation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical cycloplegic drops\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to relieve pain by paralyzing the ciliary muscle and preventing ciliary spasm, but they are not the initial management step for alkali burns.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A chemical injury to the eye should first of all be treated by irrigation with normal saline.","Alkali burns to the eye are more severe than acid burns due to deeper penetration and require immediate attention."],"references":["Chau JP, Lee DT, Lo SH. Eye irrigation for patients with ocular chemical burns: a systematic review. JBI Libr Syst Rev. 2010;8(12):470-519. doi: 10.11124/01938924-201008120-00001. PMID: 27819881. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27819881/","Sharma N, Kaur M, Agarwal T, Sangwan VS, Vajpayee RB. Treatment of acute ocular chemical burns. Surv Ophthalmol. 2018 Mar-Apr;63(2):214-235. doi: 10.1016/j.survophthal.2017.09.005. Epub 2017 Sep 19. PMID: 28935121. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28935121/","Bunker DJ, George RJ, Kleinschmidt A, Kumar RJ, Maitz P. Alkali-related ocular burns: a case series and review. J Burn Care Res. 2014 May-Jun;35(3):261-8. doi: 10.1097/BCR.0b013e31829b0037. PMID: 23877138. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23877138/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63087"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12644"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63087"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T14:25:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T19:32:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5127"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77574"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":